<br>
I'm going to use the crude basketball/baseball analogy in order to illustrate the points said.  It's by no means perfect.<br>
<br>
In baseball or basketball you play for your objectives, whatever they may be, and you have fun playing for those objectives.  Score as many runs as you want, make as many baskets as you can, whatever.  You do what you can to win those games within the rules.<br>
<br>
Now, there's a difference between being a cheat and being a good sportsman.  If somebody beats you to a spawn, you lost they won.  Don't equate that to being an @#%$.  An @#%$ is somebody who doesn't display good sportsmanship by bitching about losing or is a complete @#%$ about winning for no good reason.<br>
<br>
My point is being nice doesn't equate to sharing everything.  You don't play a basketball game to each have the same number of points so that there are no losers and you all go home happy.  That's mediocrity.  The world is FULL of competition around every turn.  Get over it and get used to it, because it's the competition that is the fun part.  If you want mediocrity go play diablo with an invincibility mod so you're always the winner and have fun if that's what you find fun.<br>
<br>
It's like you're playing basketball and you're trying to score as many points as you can, BUT when somebody on the other team falls down you don't start kicking them, calling them names or being a jerk.<br>
<br>
This is what Montague is trying to say.  You're here to play a game, that doesn't mean you try to let the other guy score as many points as you do so you can all be cool.<br>
<br>
However, like raluvin is saying, that's no reason for you to be a bad sport.  You can work out rules yourself or whatever.  But as long as things are within the rules, you have no right to be a bad sport about things, call names, or be a bigot just because you lost.  That's a good way to just piss people off more and have them be unsportsmanlike to you.<br>
